1. Introduction¶

Movie is a combination of technology, industry and art. As an international media, it is bound to the global art trends and international film market. The artistry, economy and culture of movies are inseparable from people's lives. Therefore, from the perspective of cultural transmission and economic development, we need to conduct in-depth research on the development trend of movies, so as to better promote them.

The use the dataset https://www.kaggle.com/carolzhangdc/imdb-5000-movie-dataset from Kaggle. This file contains metadata of 5000 movies from 1916 to 2016. Data points include:

  • Color (Color or 'Black and White')
  • Director_name (name of the director)
  • Num_critic_for_reviews (Number of critical reviews on Imdb)
  • Duration (how long is the movie)
  • Director_facebook_likes (likes on director’s facebook)
  • Actor_1_name
  • Actor_1_facebook_likes
  • Actor_2_name
  • Actor_2_facebook_likes
  • Actor_3_name
  • Actor_3_facebook_likes
  • Gross (gross earning of the movie)
  • Budget (budget for the film production)
  • Genres (genres of the movie, separated by | if it has more than 1)
  • Movie_title
  • Num_voted_users (Number of users who voted)
  • Cast_total_facebook_likes (Sum of facebook likes of the whole cast)
  • Facenumber_in_poster (number of people in the poster)
  • Plot_keywords (key words related to the movie)
  • Movie_imdb_link
  • Num_user_for_reviews
  • Language
  • Country
  • Content_rating
  • Title_year (The relaese year of the movie)
  • Imdb_score
  • Aspect_ratio
  • Movie_facebook_likes

Our goal is to tidy the movie data provided above and figure out what makes a movie successful.

We consider a movie successful if it has a relatively high IMDB sore or gross earning. Often only one of these two criteria can be satisfied, and many factors are taken into account to determine a movie's IMDB score or gross. Such factors can include genres, popularity of director and actors, etc.

This tutorial is going to explore how the factors contribute to the IMDB score or gross of a movie, and then make a comparison between IMDB score and gross with respect to these factors.

We used python3 with the following libraries:

  • Pandas: a tool for data structures and data analysis
  • Numpy: used for scientific computing, such as linear algebra and random number capabilities

  • Math: used for some common math functions and constants
  • Matplotlib: a library for plotting histograms, scatterplots, power spectra, etc

3.3 Organize the Dataset¶

The columns of the dataset is unsorted and hard to understand. We have to reorganize the order of columns to make the dataset easy to read.

In detail, the columns are rearranged in a way that the most important categories, such as movie title, imdb_score, gross, and budget, come before other categories. In addition, we combined the columns "director_facebook_likes", facebook_likes of actor 1, actor 2, actor 3, as well as the movie_facebook_likes into a single column.

4. Data Exploration and Visualization¶

4.1 Explore the relationship between budget, rating and gross¶

4.1.1 Gross vs Budget¶

Is there a relationship between the budget and the gross? We will figure it by the scatter plots. First, we need to check if there exists any outliers.

The box plot is a method of graphically representing a group of digital data by the number of quartiles. A box diagram also have lines that extend vertically from the box to indicate changes beyond the upper and lower quartiles. Thus, we use the boxplot to check outliers.

In [7]:
# From this graph, we can see there is one outlier in the 1.2*le10. And some outliers
# between 0.2 and 0.4*le10. Thus, we decide to set the range of budget < 0.3*le10.
seaborn.boxplot(x=movies['budget'])
movies1 = movies[movies["budget"]<300000000]

Then we want to explore the relationship between budget and gross earning. This is, does a higher budget of a movie leads to a higher gross earning? To figure out this, we do a scattered plot of budget and gross, where the budget of each movie on the x-axis, and the gross earning on the y-axis. Then we use the linear regression model to plot a best fit line to see the general relationship.

In [8]:
grossbudplot = movies1[['gross', 'budget']]
grossbudplot.plot(kind = 'scatter', y = 'gross', x = 'budget',figsize = (15,6), title = "Gross vs Budget" )
model1 = LinearRegression()
model1.fit(movies1[['budget']],movies1['gross'])
a1 = np.linspace(min(movies1['budget']),max(movies1['budget']),100)
a2 = model1.coef_*a1 + model1.intercept_
plt.plot(a1, a2, color='red')
plt.show()

According the graph above, it shows that the budget for most movies is under 100,000,000 dollors. The majority of movie's grosses is under 200,000,000 dollors. Although some points are distributed very far away from the best fit line, we can still see that budget and gross are somehow related. The line shows that there is a positive linear correlation between film budget and the gross. This means that more budget are more likely to lead to a higher gross.

4.1.2 Gross vs IMDB Score¶

We just had some ideas about the relationship between budget and gross from the previous part. Now we want to know : does a movie with a higher midb score mean it has a higher gross earning? To do this, we do a similar plot with imdb score on x-axis and gross earning on the y-axis. A best fit line is provided by linear regression to show the relationship of these two.

In [9]:
# scatter plot to show the relationship between gross and IMDB score
grossIMDBplot = movies[['gross', 'imdb_score']]
grossIMDBplot.plot(kind = 'scatter', y = 'gross', x = 'imdb_score',figsize = (15,6), title = "Gross vs IMDB score" )
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(movies[['imdb_score']],movies['gross'])
aa1 = np.linspace(min(movies['imdb_score']),max(movies['imdb_score']),100)
aa2 = model.coef_*aa1 + model.intercept_
plt.plot(aa1, aa2, color='red')
plt.show()

From the plot we can tell: scores of high-gross movies are generally range from 6 to 9. There is a best fit line with positive slope, which potentially means higher score leads to higher gross. However, we can see the high-score & low-gross part is very dense. Thus, we need a violin plot to clearly show the distribution of these points:

In [37]:
scores = [round(x) for x in movies['imdb_score']]
movies['rounded_score'] = scores
ax = seaborn.violinplot(x=movies['rounded_score'], y=movies['gross'])

From this violin plot we can see, most of the movies have a low gross earning regardless of their imdb scores. A movie with a low score( score < 5 ) always has low gross earning, and a movie with high score ( score >= 5) also not necessarily lead to a high gross. Large amount of them still have a low gross. Only very few examples fit the statement: higher score leads to higher gross. The positive slope of the best fit line above might just be the product of the fact that, there is no low score movies that has high gross. Thus, we can conclude that there is no clear relationship between score and gross.

We also want to see the change of gross over years. We will use mean gross each year as a standard to represent our data, where year is on the x-axis and the mean gross is on the y-axis. A best fit line is provided by linear regression model to show the general trends.

plt.show()

From the plot and the best fit line, we can see the mean gross generally increases each year. This can be the result of many factors, like people's improvements on life standard and better film making technologies.

4.2 Analysis on Genres¶

Distribution of Genres Over Years:¶

Next we will take a look at how the genres were distributed in each year. More specifically, for each genre, we will calculate the number of movies that the genre is categorized into annually. To do this, we need to collect information from the dataframe and process it.

As the dataframe was displayed above, we can see that the 'genres' category contains a collection of genres for each movie, so it's time to split them! In the meantime, we can add them to a set of genres, which is useful for later analysis.

In [17]:
genres = []
genre_set = set()

for g in movies['genres']:
  splitted = g.split('|')
  genres.append(splitted)
  for i in splitted:
    genre_set.add(i)

#movies['genres'] = genres
movies.loc[:, 'genres'] = genres

After we have the 'genres' holding lists of genres, we can do some calculation. The for loop after initialization computes sums, and the next one makes a lineplot accordingly.

(The default colors for line plots are not sufficient for our long list of genres. So, to avoid duplicates of color representation of the lines, we used the rainbow function from matplotlib.cm to generate unique rainbow colors for each genre.)

In [18]:
# initialization
genres_totalCount = dict()
genres_hash = dict()
years_total = dict()
for i in genre_set:
    genres_hash[i] = dict()
for i in movies['title_year'].unique():
    years_total[i] = 0

# sums up number of genre appearence each year
for i, j in movies.iterrows():
    for genre in j['genres']:
        if genre in genres_totalCount:
            genres_totalCount[genre] += 1
        else:
            genres_totalCount[genre] = 1
        years_total[j['title_year']] += 1
    if j['title_year'] in genres_hash[genre]:
        genres_hash[genre][j['title_year']] += 1
    else:
        genres_hash[genre][j['title_year']] = 1

cnt = 0
colors = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(genre_set)))
for genre, years_cnt in genres_hash.items():
    years = list(years_cnt.keys())
    counts = list(years_cnt.values())

    seaborn.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(11.7,8.27)})
    ax = seaborn.lineplot(x=years, y=counts, label=genre, c=colors[cnt])
    ax.set_title("Genre Distribution Versus Year")
    ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
    cnt += 1

A pie chart is also plotted to make a better visualization of the major distribution of the genres. To make such pie chart, a new DataFrame is created so that genres can be stored as index of the DataFrame and total counts of each genre are stored in column.

In [19]:
genres_col = []

It turns out that simply using the number of occurrence of the genres in all movies is not the best way to describe distribution over years since the number of movies each year recorded in the dataset varies. As a result, the trend of each genre's over year might be misleading. So intead, we will calculate the ratio that a specific genre appears in movies with respect to the number of movies recorded each year.

In [20]:
cnt = 0
for genre, years_cnt in genres_hash.items():
    years = list(years_cnt.keys())
    counts = list(years_cnt.values())
    ratio = []

    # Compute genres' ratio
    for i in range(len(years)):
        ratio.append(counts[i] / years_total[years[i]])

    seaborn.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(11.7,8.27)})
    ax = seaborn.lineplot(x=years, y=ratio, label=genre, c=colors[cnt])
    ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc=2, borderaxespad=0.)
    ax.set_title("Genre Distribution Versus Year")
    ax.set(xlabel='year', ylabel='ratio')
    cnt += 1

4.3 Popularity / Facebook Likes¶

Of course people would like to watch a movie directed by their favorite director, or the one with their favorite actors involved. So popularity of director or actors of the movies might directly relate to its gross, and that's going to be our next step. In this section, we are going to find and discuss the relationship between a movie's gross and the popularity of its director and main actors. There can be various ways to represent popularity, and we choose to use the number of facebook likes. In the previous sections, we extracted and combined the facebook likes of the movie itself, director, actor 1, actor 2, and actor 3. So we can start from there!

5. Comparing Gross and IMDB Score with Regression¶

5.1 Linear Regression with Interactive Terms¶

From all of our previous exploration on the data with respect to the relationship between several factors and the gross, there's no significant findings since the correlations seem to be very weak. We believe that there has to be some way, might be interactive, that these factor, when measured together, contribute to the gross or the IMDB score.

Here, to determine a relationship between gross and multiple factors, we introduce the following equation:

$$ \textit{gross} = \hat{\beta_0} + \hat{\beta_1} \times year + \hat{\beta_2} \times popularity + \hat{\beta_3} \times budget + \sum_{i=1}^{len(genres)} \hat{\beta_{3+i}} \times \delta_{g(i)} + \sum_{i=1}^{len(genres)} \hat{\beta_{3+len(genres)+i}} \times year \times \delta_{g(i)} $$

$g(i)$ gives the specific genre in the genre_set.

In the equation, the independent variables include year, popularity, budget, genre, and interactive terms of genre and year.

$g(i)$ gives the specific genre in the genre_set, and the genre_set is shown below:

In [24]:

The genres of each movie is computed with 0 and 1, and the interactive term is computed with the genre vector multiplied by the year. Then we create a new dataframe with only independent and dependent variables needed in the equation.

In [25]:
# Initialization
genres_list = []
inter_list = []
X = []

for i, j in movies.iterrows():
    glst = []
    for idx in range(len(genre_set)):
        l = list(genre_set)
        
        # glst computes genres vector
        if l[idx] in j['genres']:
            glst.append(1)
        else:
            glst.append(0)
            
    # inter_list adds interactive terms
    inter_term = [x * j['title_year'] for x in glst]
    inter_list.append(inter_term)
    genres_list.append(glst)
    xlst = list()
    xlst.append(j['title_year'])
    xlst.append(j['overall_facebook_likes'])
    xlst.extend(glst)
    xlst.extend(inter_term)
    X.append(xlst)


df = pd.DataFrame({'year':movies['title_year'], 'popularity':movies['overall_facebook_likes'], 'genres':genres_list,
                  'genre_year':inter_list,'dependent_vars': X, 'gross':movies['gross'], 'imdb_score':movies['imdb_score']})

The correlation coefficients turned out to be not as high as expected, so the linear regressions only suggest a relatively weak correlation between the indepedent variable and dependent variable.

However, we can still gain other intuition from the coefficients of the 2 models. By looking at the coefficients, we can see obvious differences, and this indicates that factors are weighted differently in determining gross and IMDB scores.

5.2 T-Test on the regressions¶

We can also make a t test with 2 sets of coefficients for comparison:

In [28]:
stats.ttest_rel(reg_gross.coef_, reg_score.coef_)
Out[28]:
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-0.6283370040474968, pvalue=0.5331066040621013)

Without surprise, the pvalue is large, inferring that gross and IMDB scores are determined very differently from the same factors.

6. Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, after cleaning and tidying up the data, we started by focus on looking at the data with respect to specific categories including gross, IMDB score, genres, etc. They don't show great relationships independently. For example, there's no clear relationship between IMDB score and gross earning, and high popularity doesn't necessarily lead to high gross. Then we tried to explore the data when we put multiple independent variables (e.g. budget, year, genre, popularity) together into a single linear equation with interaction terms of year and genre. What we actually learned is that the standards for determining gross and IMDB score differ, probably greatly, and then it turns out to be quite reasonable that movies with high IMDB score don't necessarily tend to have high gross.

We failed to compute a very precise model to determine either gross or the IMDB score this time, but this field is worth exploring. There exist too many factors which might influence a movie's quality, either measured with gross or IMDB score. These factors can include larger-scale ones like the overall economic situation of the era, or change of people's aethetic standard overtime. Some of these are hard to determine, and further data exploration and analysis can be made on other potential factors or models.
